Anyway, still find Uber to be one of the most fascinating companies of all time and, having watched Dara for years at Expedia, am very curious to see how he evolves the strategy and what it does to the P/L.

I would've guessed a steady state margin at 15-20%. To get there, need S&M + Support + R&D to be a total of 30-35%. Can't drive R&D much below 10%. So S&M+Support has to = 20-25% total, or Gross Margins have to go way higher than 60%, which seems unlikely given trajectories.

So what I'm saying is I don't understand Uber's expense structure. And it's not "Lol this is a non profit funded by VCs". They obviously have a roadmap to profitability. My question is which expense lines are they going to massively scale. My guess is S&M has to come down to 10%.

Realistically, since I am using a steady state margin, I should use more of a steady state multiple. Let's say 15x. To get to $100B need $6.7B in EBITDA and $95B in revs. $95B in revs is about $450B in gross bookings.  Priceline will do about $110B in gross bookings next year.

Softbank just bought in at ~$50B, they def want to IPO at $100B+. Let's say they get valued at 25x EBITDA, because why not, need $4B in EBITDA. At a 7% margin, that's $57B in revs.  It looks like they will do ~$8B this year.
Support is currently running 18.4% of revs. Say that scales to 10-15%. Gives you a steady state margin of 4.5-9.5% and a midpoint of 7%.  https://t.co/76Bh7uEvyA

If I close my eyes, I would imagine Uber's expenses as % of revs looks like:  40% COGS 20-25% S&M 10-15% R&D 5-7% G&A  Which results in a 19% margin. But with Operations and Support not accounted for, totally changes steady state margins.

1. Gross margin has deteriorated, opposite of what would expect from scale  2. S&M has leveraged and is about inline with internet cos  3. R&D looks a little high as % of revs  4. G&A hasn't leveraged and is way too high  5. WTF is operations and support and why isn't it in COGS?  https://t.co/s8odbfDmfH

You can put them into a spreadsheet side by side, and look at the expense items as a percentage of net revenues to get a sense for evolution of the P/L as Uber gained scale. Obviously a few things jump out.  https://t.co/Xvwo69KPAF

Getting pushback that WACC should go up with lower tax rates, so I guess I could skip the entire middle section, and say, it this way, ROIC to WACC spread is so wide right now that any viable project is likely being funded. Tax cuts won't change that.

But to summarize, my belief is that the impact of changes in cost of capital on corporate marginal propensity to invest decreases the wider the spread between ROIC hurdles and WACC, and today the spread is already very wide.

Of course it is plausible there are second order impacts. There are efficiency gains from simplifying corp tax code, particularly releasing trapped global income.  And increased divs/buybacks, higher stock prices, etc may cause increased spending leading to more demand.

That is, the gating item to increasing corporate investment today is not cost of capital or access to capital, it is a deficiency of projects meeting return hurdles. Lower tax rates thus lower WACC likely will have little first order impact on this dynamic.

Bloomberg calcs average WACC for the Russell 3000 at 7.9%. Given there is already 200bps and prob closer to 300-400bps spread between hurdle rates and cost of capital, one can conclude that any project corporations believe should be pursued can be funded.

Most operating companies that I‚Äôm familiar with set their investment hurdle rates at a minimum of 10% and mostly in the low double digits, irrespective of their WACC (REITs and other highly levered by nature businesses are an exception).

A significant reduction in corp tax rates reduces WACC, which should significantly increase the marginal propensity to invest. But I am skeptical that at this moment in time that is the case, because I think reality is conditional.
So in theory, if the return of a project is WACC + .01, corporations should pursue it. Thus, even small changes in WACC should yield significant changes in investment by corporations.
Basic finance theory calculates WACC via cost of equity, cost of debt and cap structure. Theory also states that investing where ROIC > WACC is value creating.

A quick stream of conscience on cost of capital, corporate tax rates and the marginal propensity to invest. I assume there is academic literature on the subject but I am removed from those days, and this is based on 15 years of dealing with co‚Äôs.

Tinder's valuation was determined by outside I-Banks. Historically the market has assumed 8-10x sales, but on a much smaller sales number.
If you assume Rad owned around 8-10% of Tinder, you get an implied valuation of $3.5-4B for Tinder.
Interestingly, last week, Sean Rad filed a 13D in Match. Rad's stake in Tinder converted into 21.7M Match shares, roughly $400M.  https://t.co/fN12uEON0R
By next year, you can get Tinder revs of $500M+, approaching 1/3 of all Match revenue.  So what's that worth?

And when you see journos of all stripes opining on the death of ESPN, you take notice.
However, question today is does this matter as much as it did 2 years ago? I dunno, but surely the market has internalized ESPNs struggles.
None of this should be controversial! It's fairly self evident, cable nets ROIC > studio/parks. Cable nets ROIC will fall. These are facts.
So two things have happened, the quality of cable nets biz has deteriorated and will continue to, and lesser quality biz have become larger.
As Studio/Parks have grown in % of earnings, the quality of DIS earnings stream has degraded. Studio/Parks are good biz, but not phenomenal.
As for Disney, part of its premium the last 10+ years was that a substantial portion of it's earnings came from a phenomenal business, ESPN.
But, it will have fewer subs, higher price point, higher churn, higher SG&A costs, and be an economically inferior business.
In the future there will likely be an aggregator of sports rights, it will get paid lots of sub fees and ad revs. It will likely be ESPN.
But, important point! Economically worse does not mean the death of ESPN, the implosion of ESPN, or anything else like that.
The simple truth is the linear model was phenomenally good for ESPN. Whatever the future looks like is near certain to be economically worse
But I have never argued ESPN was going to collapse or any of the crazy things that have been written in the last 2 days.
For years I have argued ESPN will face challenges in the transition from linear TV to DTC model. I felt the narrative was far too optimistic
